A year ago, I was diagnosed with stage 4 Small Bowel Cancer. Christmas has always been my favorite time of the year and is always filled with warmth and happiness. So, having Taylor tell me I have cancer on Christmas was beyond life—shattering. 

Many have asked how I’m doing and if I’m prepared for the first anniversary. I choose not to view this as an “anniversary”, but rather a day that has shaped the way I will live my life.This shift in perspective is not an easy one.Instead of allowing Christmas to be forever tainted, I’m choosing to celebrate that God allowed a tumor to form so we could catch the cancer, how I’m now cancer-free, and that I’m alive spending the holiday with my family.This year and been filled up many ups and downs.The wildest rollercoaster I’ve ever been on! The trauma from this year has been incredibly challenging. I’ve been struggling with depression, anxiety, flashbacks, intrusive thoughts, and difficultly figuring out my new sense of “normalcy.” It’s common for people to assume that everything goes back to “normal” after a no evidence of disease (NED) outcome.But this is just another chapter in my story.I’m clear for now and can only pray that it continues this way. For now, it’s truly one day at a time.

The hardest lesson I’ve learned this year is loving myself more. I appreciate my body more now than I ever have.This body endured numerous rounds of chemotherapy, 3 surgeries, various scans/ tests, and a 12inch incision down my stomach. My scars tell a story and serve as a reminder that I am a survivor. I am proud of my scars and will be eternally grateful that this body has saved my life. 

To wrap up this year, Taylor and I celebrated in the best way we know how - a trip to Disney World! I walked over 50 miles in 7 days; something I could not have accomplished 3 months ago. We had the most magical time 💫

This Christmas please tell your friends/family how much they mean to you. Cherish those traditions you’ve created and celebrate life and love. Make time this next year to do something for you. Life can change in an instant, so appreciate each moment you have.
#fuckcancer #stage4cancer #smallbowelcancer #mdandersoncancercenter

Cancer Update 💜Scans on 3/1 indicated a reoccurrence.A cyst on my right ovary had doubled since December a few spots my lungs grew & an enlarged lymph node at the jejunum.During our trip to Hawaii, I was told the surgeon would remove the right ovary & begin chemotherapy after.I met with the surgeon on 3/14 & he said he intended to remove both ovaries & do a full hysterectomy.We weren’t given an option explanation as to why when there was no evidence of disease elsewhere.We asked about egg preservation we were told that it was not an option as Oncofertility at MDA had a 6-8 week waiting period.Same day my oncologist told me that I’ve already exceeded my life expectancy & most people with met 4 SBC are looking at months to a year to live.That information is inaccurate & untrue based on other SBC fighters, medical journals & I don’t fit the traditional stats because of my age.The news was utterly shocking & devastating.My interactions with the surgeon & oncologist left me feeling disregarded, dismissed, unheard & treated like a number rather than a person.Taylor & I were in crisis mode & decided we need a second opinion.Taylor found a surgeon specializing in GI cancers & HIPEC at UCHealth.Knowing the positive experience my mother-in-law had at UCHealth,we felt this was the place to seek a second opinion.Judy made a phone call on Tuesday afternoon & by Thursday the surgeon had accepted me.UCHealth put in an urgent referral to Oncofertility & I was seen Monday.I met with the surgeon & oncologist on Wednesday.Within a week, my entire treatment plan changed & we had more options.I felt like a person.I was given options, treated with compassion, empathy & given hope.Their survival statistics are higher & they are incredibly proactive.I keep saying “just keep me in the game & I’ll continue to fight. Don’t take me out.”My surgery at UCHealth to remove the right ovary & possibly the left one is scheduled for 4/10.Prayers that my left ovary is unaffected by the disease!

Beauty in the face of Adversity 
It’s hard to articulate the range of emotions @mrsjesspryor and I have experienced over the past 17 months. Through the ups and downs, it’s imperative to stay positive. As we begin the new chapter at UCHealth, that’s the daily reminder. Stay positive. Control what you can control. We are praying for a smooth surgery tomorrow with a quick recovery. We are confident in the oncology team and the treatment options they have provided. Jessica is ready to get back on the road to NED. We appreciate all the love and support 🙏🏼 
Before heading up to Colorado, Jessica and I went storm chasing together last weekend. We were treated to a beautiful supercell just south of Stephenville. It was a wonderful moment to share together.

✅ #2 round of chemo complete 

Fantastic news… tumor markers went down by 2 points! Considering my CEA levels are low… 2 points is considerable! 12.1 ➡️ 10.1! 

Chemo is working! It’s always nerve racking switching regimens and just hoping that it will work. 

All my blood work looked fantastic - white blood cell count was still in normal range. Always a concern when on chemo. 

Overall, I’ve felt great since my first infusion and hoping it continues to stay that way 💪 

Thank you to everyone for the well-wishes, prayers, and support 💜

Denver Nights⚡️
Here’s a long exposure shot from the drone last night. Very impressed with the quality given this was an 8 second exposure from 390ft in the air. 
Rain and storms have been a common occurrence over the past couple months. Denver has experienced record breaking rainfall since May. The jet stream has remained further south limiting the severity in northern Colorado, due to El Niño, but that doesn’t mean these storms can’t pack a punch from time to time.

Denver Nights⚡️
I didn’t chase much last week, but I did enjoy seeing storms from the backyard. If you look closely, you can see a plane (yellowish streak) in between the two lightning strikes on the right hand side. The @hasselblad on the @djiglobal drone has been a game changer. These lightning strikes were captured at 250ft in 15-20 mph of winds. Typically, when doing long exposures, the camera sensor has to be perfectly still. This really speaks to the steadiness of the drone and gimbal. I also captured the Highlands Ranch EF-1 tornado, via the drone, last week as well.

The Green Sea Turtle 
Poipu is one of the best areas on Kauai to witness beautiful sea life. Where seals and sea turtles come to rest each day and night. You can also see hundreds of different species of fish. I was fortunate to swim with turtles on various occasions this trip, but the most impactful experience was without my camera. 
Back story: Our great friends, unbeknownst to us, planned their anniversary trip to Kauai the same time we were there. So Jacob, my best man, invited me to spearfish with him. Considering I would be holding a gun, I decided to leave the camera. We went to an area off the coastline in Koala. I spent 3 hours straight enjoying pristine coral reefs and various turtles. I swam with one young turtle in particular for at least 5 minutes. Just the two of us in the surf with a rainbow overhead. 
The experience reminded me of a scene from The Secret Life of Walter Mitty where Sean Penn’s character just watches a snow leopard in amazement. “If I like a moment, I mean; me, personally, I don't like to have the distraction of the camera. I just want to stay in it. Right there... Right here.”
That quote truly resonates and this was a moment I will always remember.
Honestly, I was just glad I didn’t cramp up. Since we went from the shoreline, there were no breaks during the dive. We swam out almost a quarter mile offshore through the surf. I also didn’t know this area is considered one of the hardest areas to spearfish. 
And don’t worry, no sea-life was injured by my spear. 
Be sure to support recovery efforts in Maui, by following the link  https://www.mauinuistrong.info/support
This is the deadliest wildfire the US has seen in over a century. There will be long term recovery and rebuilding efforts and they will need our help for months to come.

Nāpali Magic 🪄 
Don’t be fooled by “champagne sailing” on the north shore of Kaua’i. If you are drinking champagne, be sure to hold on tight because it’s going to be a bumpy ride. Even on the calmer days, swells will reach 5+ ft. In the winter, well let’s just say it isn’t for the faint of heart. While most people were bracing their drinks and themselves, I was wielding my phone and camera without straps. Probably not the smartest idea, but then again, I wasn’t necessarily planning on a 4 hour sailing adventure coming into the trip. I’d say it was worth the risk. Although, my opinion would differ if I’d dropped one of them in the Pacific. Since we didn’t get to see the full sunset from the Nāpali Coast, here’s my interpretation. 
-If you’re interested in this once in a lifetime experience, be sure to checkout @capt.andys. A+ service and the nicest catamarans on the island.

NāPali from Above 🚁 
One thing Jessica and I said we’d never do is fly in a helicopter, but I did some research earlier in the year just incase the moment arrived. So when my parents brought it up in Kauai, Jessica said “forget it, let’s do it!” I timidly agreed, but said “if we do it, we’re going to do it right.” The tour I research earlier in the year is the only tour that has the rights to fly over and land at one of the most remote and iconic waterfalls in the world. Yes, the famous Manawaiopuna Falls “Jurassic Falls” featured in the original Jurassic Park. This area of Kauai is so remote, in order to preserve and prevent outside contamination, you have to wear shoe covers when walking around the falls. Truly a once in a lifetime experience.

Supercell at Sunset
I miss seeing sights like this in Texas. Hopefully we’ll see some drought and heat relief over the next few days. This tornado warned supercell turned over the countryside for more then 2 hours creating a beautiful barbers 💈 structure. If you look at the right side of the image, you’ll notice an inflow band of clouds feeding into the rotating updraft. While on the left side, clouds are moving from left to right wrapping around the base of the meso. Great visual representation of a powerful supercell.

Happy birthday to the most amazing woman in the world @mrsjesspryor. I am so lucky to have you in my life. Even though the past couple of years haven’t been what we envisioned, it haven’t stop you from living. If anything, it has made us live and not just exist. You’re a constant inspiration, so I thought I’d write a few lines about life and adversity. 

Living in the face of adversity,
A challenge that we all must face,
For in the darkness, you find your light,
And in the shadows, your strength is born.
The winds of change may blow with might,
But you must stand tall and never shy in fright,
For every stormy sky, a rainbow shines bright,
And in the tempest, a chance to soar.
The trials you face, they make you strong,
And in the flame, your spirit glows,
For adversity, it tests your will,
And in the test, your character grows.
So let you not be daunted or dismayed,
For in the face of adversity, you shall find the way,
And though the path be long and hard,
You’ll rise above, and never fall. 
For you are strong, stronger than you know. And always know, I love you so. 
Happy Birthday @mrsjesspryor
